One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he slipped into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a nearby election commission building, and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on the football field outside the local police station and army headquarters, demanding justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita dance - in which one runs in a circle and imitates the singing of birds - of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe.
Several Protestants began throwing rocks at the buildings.
With tensions mounting, the soldiers were ordered over the radio: "If the mob tries to resist at least three times, you are cleared to fire," according to TIME, in an official document whose contents were never published in the local media.
Yeremias Kayame (56), head of the Enarotali district Kego Koto, recognised the danger and urged residents to disperse to their homes.
But no one heeded his words.
"When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist," he told TIME Weekly on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame does not yet know who the shooter was, but in his words, the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
"There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting," he added.
