Only 13 countries have visa-free travel with China; the citizens of the others have to process their visas in advance.
At Chinese offices in the US, the crowds are therefore comparable to Chinese New Year celebrations.
A visa costs $140, but if you don't want to wait long hours in line, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions erect significant economic barriers.
A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for a visa reduces a country's visitor numbers by 70 percent.
Only two million Americans visited mainland China in 2015, while 1.8 million Americans visited Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China's gross domestic product and has less than one percent of its population.
China often exacerbates the problem itself by using tourism to achieve its policy goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China cut traffic to South Korea in the spring amid a rift over South Korea's anti-missile system, the South Koreans hit back, avoiding China.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent year-on-year, while Japan saw an increase of 85 percent.
All this affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recently published report by the US Federal Reserve, as much as $190 billion may have left China as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China receives about $35 billion annually in currency sales to incoming tourists.
According to official balance of payments figures, China had a $217 billion deficit in tourism last year, equal to 44 percent of China's total surplus in trade in goods.
So the small number of tourists deals a very painful blow to a country that is anxiously preventing capital flight.
But the factors listed above are only one manifestation of a more general reticence toward outsiders.
In many parts of China, immigrants have been virtually unheard of.
As recently as 2013, there were fewer than a million foreigners across China.
Some individual cities have more in the United States.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has double that.
Meanwhile, many scientific papers show that immigrants tend to revive economic growth, entrepreneurship, and innovation.
But they are virtually impossible to find in China.
Solving these problems will be politically challenging, but the step at hand is to simplify the visa apparatus.
Other Asian states, notably India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to make visa procedures simpler and cheaper.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currency, it should be easier for them to get there.
