Moore's Ford Bridge massacre: activists commemorate racist lynching
A 1948 Ford Mercury passed bystanders in Monroe, Georgia, and lurched toward Moore's Ford Bridge.
But before the car, carrying four black passengers and a white driver, could reach the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its way.
The leader of the group - a middle-aged man in a striped suit - took a long drag on his cigarette and stared at the windshield of the automobile.
Inside, the passengers trembled with fear.
"We want that n---a Roger!" the man yelled.
"Bring it to me!"
The silence is broken by the roar of a young black man being pulled from the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this scene is merely a reconstruction of the events that occurred on July 22.
But when one of the men throws a noose over "Roger's" neck, the audience sighs with excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists have been returning regularly to Moore's Ford Bridge, reconstructing the fateful night in 1946 when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by Kukluxklan members.
No one has ever been tried for the murders.
"It's surprising that not a single person has been arrested in all these years - even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identities," said Tyrone Brooks, who is helping to organize the reconstruction of the event.
"It's a stain on our history and a burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and lifelong civil rights campaigner.
In his eyes, the reenactment of the event represents a dramatic call to action, reminding the community of Monroe each year that justice has not been served.
"We demand prosecution and closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all," said Brooks.
"Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin."
A medical examiner covers one of the bodies of the victims of the Moore's Ford lynching on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were expected to participate in the lynching.
But no one has yet been prosecuted.
Despite suspects remaining at large for decades, civil rights supporters argue that both reasons for lynching - politics and sex - were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision gave Georgia's black residents the right to participate for the first time ever in an election that had been scheduled for the summer.
And it was during the summer election season, according to the FBI, that black farmer Roger Malcom was supposed to stab white landowner Barnett Hester during a scuffle - allegedly over his wife.
In town, according to Brooks, it was said that Hester had made love to Malcom's wife, Dorothy, and got her pregnant.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, then-prominent white landowner Loy Harrison posted $600 bail for Malcom.
He was accompanied to the prison by Dorothy and cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
On their return from the prison, just before the entrance to Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects blocked their way.
“As it turns out, the murders were planned and orchestrated by Harrison,” the FBI concluded.
"It is also clear that there was collusion between state and local law enforcement officials who not only participated in the lynching, but also disposed of evidence and concealed the identity of witnesses."
Brooks was more succinct about the matter.
"It was a massacre over the right to vote," he said.
"The murders had a clear subtext for all black locals: 'this is what you get if you register and vote'."
The annual reconstruction of the Moore's Ford Bridge event has been organized by Cassandra Greene for nearly a decade.
Her performance is figurative, engaging, and apt, showing a deep-seated racism that many would like to think extinct in modern America.
Watching this reconstruction isn't easy, and it's even more difficult to look away, but Greene says it makes sense.
"No one wants to talk about lynching because in doing so we have to face the uncomfortable feelings that lurk within each of us," Greene said.
"But there can be no relationship between us unless you listen to what I've been through."
The main rehearsals for this year's reenactment began in June, and on the first day, approximately 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - crowded into a room where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh is acting assistant director.
He played the leader of the Kukluxklan for many years, but in his words, the role is exhausting.
"I have a bad feeling about this because it contradicts who I am," Marbaugh said.
"I think it's very important to remember that part of history regularly, because we never want to go back to that time."
Actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play the role of Roger Malcom and, by extension, Barnett Hester, rehearse their roles.
The show begins with a scuffle - Malcom arguing with Hester and blaming him for sleeping with his wife.
"Get off my f---ing property!"
You can't take Rascon.
There's a scuffle.
At that moment, everyone (every black actor, anyway) bursts into laughter.
Greene laughs the most.
"What happened?" he asks Rascon.
He's confused.
Was I too rude?
"No," Greene says cheerfully.
"I just don't think white people said 'n-r' in that tone back then."
"Exactly," one of the black actors blurts.
"You have to put more emphasis on R."
The energy in the room is suddenly better; hostility replaces a sense of rapprochement.
Everyone wants the show to be authentic, if only for it to be done for enough of the four victims of the massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
This time, Rascona emphasizes the correct pronouncement of the N word.
Nobody's laughing now.
The show ends violently and quickly.
The screams, the gunshots... and the silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the bodies of the actors and sings a mournful Billie Holiday song, "Strange Fruit."
There's a sadness in the room with every word.
Against the background of all this, a dozen or so onlookers wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
There are virtually equal numbers of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple traveled all the way from Ithaca, New York, many of the onlookers from nearby.
They each endure the local humid climate for nearly eight hours, and Brooks leads them in line to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until now, the murders may have been viewed with detachment, but now, standing in the same spot where the lynching took place, the atmosphere is eerie.
With the last words of the song, Greene invites a crowd of onlookers to inspect the bodies.
The children kneel by the heads of the victims, watching the fake blood and the still bodies and whispering in their ears.
"They're not dead," the little boy says.
A few minutes go by and Greene thanks the audience.
The actors are cleaning the rope and wiping away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the leader of the Kukluxklan.
Nick Rascona hugs his two actor friends and bursts into tears in their arms; emotion finally comes over him.
"It's all right," whispers one of the women.
"We know you abhor the role.
But you had a reason."
Later that same day, the audience sits down with the actors for dinner.
At one table, a young Caucasian couple talks with enthusiasm about a show with a black couple they met today.
Denise Duplinski could barely find the words to express her feeling about tonight's performance.
"It's difficult to listen to those nasty words and look at the hideous deeds . . . done by people who look like you and do it because they look like you," she told the reenactment.
"It makes me realize that lynching is still an issue," she added, "it's just called police skirmishes."
Across the room, Tyrone Brooks is sitting in a courtroom, enjoying his dinner while talking about civil rights.
By his own account, he had already begun planning the show for the next year.
"The reconstruction of these events is inspiring, as it describes the fear we must have experienced - but it is also a moment for reflection," he said.
"If we don't learn from this, who knows . . . it could happen again.
People who do not know and study the history of their country are doomed to repeat it."
