How football's financial rules will affect Neymar's move to Paris
Rules restricting the financing of European football clubs will do nothing to disrupt Neymar's record transfer from Barcelona, Spain, to Paris-Saint Germain, France.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by the EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to ban teams from the prestigious Champions League.
The Financial Fair Play (FFP) rules, introduced by UEFA in 2011, stipulate that PSG will have to prove that Neymar's transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid a sum of EUR 222 million just to buy Neymar out of his contract and Neymar will demand a salary of several tens of millions of dollars a year.
There are several financial terms for Neymar's transfer to France.
Since the PSG team is financed by a wealthy Qatari family who made their fortune in energy sales, they can afford to bring Neymar into an already stellar football family.
Clubs can spend huge sums to buy players, but on the other hand they have to prove legal sources of income, which allows them to cover the overheads of commercial football-related activities.
FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after being installed as UEFA Director in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that went into debt in pursuit of new reinforcements ultimately cheated and risked bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to provide them.
In 2011, the FFP rules redirected their attention from club debt to monitoring their losses.
That change meant that the business model Roman Abramovich used with Chelsea in 2003 - buying a club with potential and spending huge sums on players to build a global brand - was suddenly not so advantageous.
Under the current three-year trial period, which ends in 2018, clubs can report a loss of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite Platini having to leave his post in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Cheferin, is determined to advocate a ban on excessive spending.
"The FFP rules are still in place and we are committed to strengthening them in the future," Andrea Traverso, who oversees FFP compliance, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid the sum for the redemption of Neymar in a lump sum payment, it may, for accounting purposes, spread the sum over the entire duration of the contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be broken down to EUR 44.4 million each year for five years.
The first wave of the highest FFP sanctions hit PSG in 2014, along with Manchester City, which is owned by the Abu Dhabi group.
PSG received a fine of EUR 60 million ($82 million) - which was later reduced to EUR 20 million - and an injunction to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is wary of teams that may attempt to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their revenues through companies associated with club owners.
Therefore, even if the Qatari company sponsors PSG once the financing exceeds the value of the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit billing.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after it decided that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to the PSG team was too high.
Some reports suggest that part of Neymar's income at PSG could be paid from the organising committee for the 2022 football in Qatar.
However, PSG and MS 2022 officials in Qatar denied the fat that Neymat should become an ambassador for MS in football and that such a manoeuvre would be easily detected by UEFY officials.
Previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules,
