"Summer to Survival" and "Comrade Detective" strike a nostalgic chord
This iteration of the story is nostalgic for both the characters of the famous 1980s; the sordid 1990s (when geniuses David Wain and Michael Showalter put a comedy sketch called "The State" on MTV); and, of course, for modern times, namely 2001, before stars like Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler, and Paul Rudd fled to bigger projects.
As a cultural artifact, it is both a light parody and the embodiment of our modern Facebook era of lasting memories.
From the perspective of the franchise, though, it looks like someone's running out of breath.
The series "First Day of Camp" worked surprisingly well - not just because of its absurd humor (an example might be the story of the creation of a talking can of vegetables by H. Jon Benjamin).
The authors moved away from the main witty punch line - middle-aged actors playing horny teenagers - and couldn't make fun of previous events.
The sequel "Ten Years Later," in which adults play adults doesn't push the emotional level as much, and the satire is sporadic in places, including a parody of 1990s thrillers like "The Hand on the Cradle."
At one point, the character finds an Apple Powerbook, roller skates, and "a lot of other stuff from 1991" in a pile of junk.
Many major storylines repeat themselves.
The good-hearted Coop (Mr. Showalter), now a writer, still hasn't gotten over his love for Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) is still a virgin.
Not to mention a crazy plot that involves Ronald Reagan (also Mr. Showalter) being egged on by George H. W. Bush (a very well-cast Michael Ian Black).
As always, the best part of the franchise is the many side stories.
Particularly amusing is watching the ever-young, long-haired Rudd, aka Matt Dillon's character from the film Youth, whose once respectable character Andy is now an old geezer.
The franchise could be triggered by moments of random madness, like the returning "Seven Up" series, until it reaches what I suspect will be a logical conclusion: "Wet Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later," when, in the final scene, the entire group goes on to premiere "Years to Survive."
Meanwhile, "Comrade Detective" on Amazon appeals to another type of nostalgia: the Cold War revivalism of "Such Normal Americans," the movie "Atomic Blonde: No Pity," and even the series "GLOW," in which icons of the East and West wrestling scenes collide.
The comedy by creators Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanak, directed by Rhys Thomas, is intended to be a television production: a drama about two Bucharest police officers from 1980s Romania fighting for truth and atheism in the manner of Marxism-Leninism.
The lead roles - the tenacious Gregor and the idealistic Iosef - are played by Florin Piersic Jr. and Corneliu Ulici, who have been drummed into the English language by Channing Tatum (the show's executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It's a wonderful idea.
Unfortunately, it's not much more than that.
You laugh at some of the jokes (like the cops watching chess on TV - a parody of American football).
Many well-known actors have lent their voices to the series - among them Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloë Sevigny.
But "Comrade Detective" focuses too much on the clumsy propaganda drama - which includes a Reagan-masked killer - and that's what it looks like.
Six long episodes are too long and comedy moments aren't enough.
At shorter notice, the propaganda satire in "Comrade Detective" might work, as in the scene where Gregor and Iosef repeatedly visit the US Embassy, in whose lobby two fat men devour hamburgers stacked in a big pile.
The clear message to an imaginary communist audience is that Western culture can turn everything into food and orgies.
The imagined Romanian creators were right: we do so with our own culture, as well as with theirs.
