NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
Patients will be given access to 'transformative' treatment to prevent HIV from September, following a Supreme Court ruling on funding for the NHS drug.
England's National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 per cent, will be offered through a health service to around 10,000 patients as part of a three-year trial period.
NSH agreed to fund the trial period after the Court of Appeal upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year stating that the NHS had the financial means to pay for PrEP despite declaring that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was taken by NHS England at the lips of director-general Simon Stevens as a 'major intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'crucial moment'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients, with more clinics joining in October and full implementation across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among patients at risk.
Applying PrEP before sex means that there are enough specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These drugs can be taken every day or for at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who will sign a consent form to participate in testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also enrol in their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The scheme will cost taxpayers £10 million and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute medicines after winning an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: 'This important intervention should complement and fully exploit the ever-expanding and increasingly successful pursuit of HIV prevention.
It's another milestone in the more than 30-year quest to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, Executive Director of the NAT (National Aids Trust) said: 'We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and patients are at risk, it will offer a chance to change England's HIV epidemic.
From September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and not subject to partner coaxing, which will improve the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to accept this statement.'
Ian Green, executive director of the Terrence Higgins Trust said: 'The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of trials across the country; we must ensure its availability to every patient.
We now have a trial drug, PrEP, and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV.'
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: 'The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delay and delay by the Government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV and, together, end the spread of HIV in society.'
