Trump's new chief of staff plans to curtail the president's media diet
Before him, many have tried and always failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can actually do it.
If so, he'll be the first.
The Politico website reported that the new chief of staff at the White House plans to restrict President Trump's flow of information - including television news stories - in hopes of keeping Trump afloat.
Here's part of reporter Josh Dawsey's report:
"When John F. Kelly, the new White House chief of staff, met with staff on his first day in the new job, he outlined a key problem for the Trump White House that he intends to fix: incorrect information coming into the president's hands.
Kelly told the staff that he had to personally approve all information - whether on paper or spoken word - because the President could make a better decision based on the right information."
Kelly's diagnosis actually makes sense, but many of his predecessors cut their teeth checking Trump and his media presentation.
Trump's relationship with the media dates back several decades - and now that he's sitting in the White House, his habit of watching TV news is even stronger.
