Michelle Carter convicted of sending text messages encouraging suicide of Conrad Roy
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two years' imprisonment for inciting her boyfriend to commit suicide by text messages and phone calls.
Twenty-year-old Michelle Carter will serve 15 months of a two-year prison sentence and then spend five years on probation.
Carter was convicted in June for the involuntary manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who took his own life on July 13, 2014.
In court on Thursday, Roy's father said, "The whole family is devastated.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was left free pending the decision.
She faced up to 20 years in prison, but her lawyers argued that she and Roy suffered from mental illness.
Dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, Carter stood where she was when the verdict was announced, tears in her eyes, hands clasped, eyes pointing to the ground.
"Her actions killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the judge.
"She ended his life to relieve herself.
She could not accept her own responsibility," she said.
"She showed no remorse."
But Carter's attorney said it was "unfortunate circumstances that she deeply regrets."
Judge Lawrence Moniz added that ‘her age or level of maturity or even mental impairment does not have a significant impact on her actions’.
The claimant read a statement from Roy's mother, Lynn Roy: "Not a day goes by that I don't mourn the loss of my son.
I want him to be proud of me - I care for his sisters and together we will endure the immense pain we will carry with us forever," the statement said.
Roy's sister, Camdyn Roy, testified that she was "haunted" by the knowledge that she would never attend her brother's wedding and would never be his children's aunt.
"The loss of a man I have been seeing since I was born is a pain I will carry with me for life," she said.
The state of Massachusetts does not have a law in place to sanction a person aiding and abetting the suicide of another person, so this case sets a legal precedent.
Carter was 17 years old when Roy was found in a car seat in 2014, poisoned by carbon dioxide.
The case drew national attention after Carter's text messages that incited suicide were released.
"Maybe hang yourself, jump off a building or stab yourself, I don't care," said text messages Carter sent just two weeks before his death while Roy was on a family vacation.
Minutes before the suicide, she texted him, "You have to do this Conrad" and "All you have to do is turn on the generator and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Moniz said that Carter wanted attention through Roy's death and ordered her to refrain from making any comments in the press.
The case raised many questions.
One of the people who sided with Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted of murdering her British roommate in Italy in 2007.
Ms. Knox (30) published a statement in the Los Angeles Times: "Michelle Carter deserves understanding and help, not jail."
