Lavender of Provence is threatened by climate change
Lavender has become a symbol of Provence in the region of south-eastern France, but is now under threat from climate change.
Lavender is declining due to a dry climate and harmful insects, causing consternation on the faces of researchers and farmers looking for solutions.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at the agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM in Provence said: "Lavender growing in Provence is under threat because over the last few years the plant has been exposed to climate changes, with less rainfall in spring and autumn.
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
Cicadas and locusts carrying micro-bacteria that thrive in dry climates are also to blame."
The stakes are high.
Lavender attracts tourists and the oil produced from it is an important ingredient in perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: 'Instead of long and beautiful flowers, smaller, undeveloped and often weak plants grow.
The amount of oil extracted from these lavenders is understandably smaller."
A possible solution may be to distribute water more efficiently and slow down the evaporation of water from the soil, but also to spray lavender with a protective mixture of clay and water, and to breed more species resistant to dry weather.
Murder of journalist highlights growing threats in Mexico
Staff of Riodoce weekly meet regularly every Wednesday to discuss the news of the riots taking place in the Sinaloa region involving organised criminals, corrupt officials and the relentless drug wars.
Today, however, under the strain of recent events, they gather mainly for their own safety.
They learn that it's important for them to change their habits.
Two well-deserved journalists talk about what would be safer: taking their children with them to an office that was attacked with a grenade in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three simple words on the black board: adversaries, neutrals, and allies.
They ask journalists to put names to every word - no evidence is needed, just use imagination and foreboding.
Picking them out of what - drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen and journalists are suspected of taking money from the government or drug cartels - a catalogue of criminals tasked with covering up criminal behaviour.
Violence continues and bodies pile up across the country; journalists continue to arrive among them: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, there are at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto came to power in December 2012; 589 journalists are under federal protection following attacks and threats; and seven have been killed this year in all seven states.
Among them was the co-founder of the periodical Riodioce, an editor and inspiration to colleagues, Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and working as a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on the violence involved in the drug trade.
His loss is palpable, though his presence is all-pervasive - a large photograph of Valdez with the word "Justice" on it, in which he gives the finger, hangs in the front of the building; two journalists - Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez - aged over 30, wearing a T-shirt with a photograph of Valdez with a smile on his face, glasses on his nose, and a Panama cap.
The meeting comes less than two months after his death; journalists talk about mutual traumas, nightmares, insomnia, and paranoia.
Even though a special federal prosecutor was established in 2010 to handle journalists' cases, it has so far sued two suspects, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
Most of the thousands of murders that occur every year are associated with drug trafficking and organized crime, so journalist killers very rarely go to trial.
Journalists from Riodoca insist on reporting on the violence happening in Sinaloa; even though they are devastated by grief and the territory is currently very treacherous.
Without information about the killers and without a vision of justice, a meeting about security is pointless, Ibarra says.
"It's foolish to waste time on meetings like this," he adds.
"Unless we get more information, nobody can be trusted."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the Riodoce headquarters in Culiacán, the capital of Sinaloa.
He managed to get several blocks away when his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men who pulled him out of the car and killed him with 12 bullets, apparently because of the title of the article - which translates as Twelfth River.
The gunmen then got into his car and crashed it not far from the scene.
Valdez died at age 50.
He left behind a wife and two grown children.
Rumours seem to be spreading fast in Culiacan.
In Valdez's case, however, there is a suspicious silence.
Since the arrest of Guzmán last year and his extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa has become one of the country's bloodiest battlegrounds as rival factions try to fill the void.
Several people are killed every day on the streets of Sinaloa, and the cemetery is filled with ornate two-story mausoleums for drug kingpins, many of them larger than houses.
Forget for a moment that the word "truce" means that one drug cartel controls a coastal state with precious ports and important routes through which drugs travel to the United States.
In spite of this, as well as the fact that Valdez was intimately acquainted with the risks of his employment, Ismail Bojorquez (60), Riodoce's co-founder and director, continues to lay bare the fact that he did not protect his friend.
He believes two wrongdoings contributed to his death.
The first was the February edition of an interview with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival drug cartels that waged war on the sons of Joaquín Guzmán.
The conciliation might have angered the sons; the suspected gang members had bought up all the copies of the newspaper the moment they landed on the counters.
The second mistake was not forcing Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after the seizure of other newspapers in which the same story was printed.
Valdez has become a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his death is viewed as an important milestone in the fight of Mexican criminals against journalists.
He had managed to survive for so long, and all his friends and colleagues believed that would never change.
He was practically a veteran in the Noroeste periodical when, in 2003, he decided to sell his $50 worth of stock and set up Riodoce with five of his colleagues.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to run a newspaper without mentioning the drug trade," said Bojorquez.
Riodoce gained a reputation over time for its brave and truthful reporting; newspapers began to prosper.
Journalists liked to dig into problem topics and publish texts without censorship - readers were fascinated to read stories no one else dared to publish.
Eight years after its founding, Riodoce won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot award for reporting on Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists for his brave reporting on Mexico's drug trade.
Valdez openly admitted he was scared.
"I feared for my life," he said as he accepted the award.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloae is a "way of life," Valdez said in an interview with Rompeviento TV in October last year.
"You have to take on the role of journalist - or play dumb.
