Salvador Adame disappeared just three days after Valdez's murder in the western part of Michoacán state.
Only the charred body was discovered, and authorities say that based on DNA analysis, it's Adame.
Journalist activity is intensifying across the country, with many organizing protests and scribbling "SOS press" on sidewalks and buildings.
The newspaper's director, Bojorquez, is visiting Washington for the day, seeking international support and justice for Valdez's death.
At a meeting with the Sinaloa governor the day after Valdez's murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of stalking journalists and murdering them for telling the truth.
Meanwhile, she requested a transfer to another department out of concern that her anger might compromise her impartiality.
Valdez has repeatedly said that Mexican journalists are being “bypassed” by organized crime, corrupt officials, and an indifferent public.
In his latest book, "Narco-journalism," he wrote that journalists die not only at the hands of drug cartels, but also at the behest of politicians and security forces who cooperate with organized crime.
The media watchdog group Articulo 19 blamed police and public officials for more than half of all attacks on journalists.
"In Mexico, you die because they want to silence you," Ramirez added.
Murders obviously work.
No one will forget the death of blogger Marie Elizabeth Macías six years ago at the northern border of Tamaulipas.
Her body was found along with a note purportedly signed by the Zetas cartel: "This is how I ended up because of my reports."
