Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however terrifying.
Researchers have now uncovered the conclusions of the first findings of an amazing rhino-sized creature whose perfectly preserved remains - what experts have called the 'Mona Lisa of dinosaurs' - were found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were preserved to such a high degree that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of its scaly skin and said the dinosaur had a 'troubled past'.
An article in the journal Current Biology said it was "the best-preserved armored dinosaur found to date and one of the best species of dinosaur in the world."
The fossil is a new species of the Nodosauridae family. The dinosaur lived during the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
His perfectly preserved condition shocked the researchers, who described it as 'truly remarkable.'
The armored white-eater is still the best preserved fossil of its kind, according to National Geographic.
Behind the find is Shawn Funk, who uncovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He came across what appeared to be a foreign object and decided to examine it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Researchers spent the next six years working to unearth the animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1100kg.
When the work is done, the dinosaur is ready to be unveiled.
"'Just squint a little and you'll believe it's asleep,' said lead researcher Caleb Brown and a naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
'It will most certainly go down in history as one of the most beautiful and tame species of dinosaur - the Mona Lisa dinosaurs.'
By studying its skin, the researchers found that this herbivore - despite being covered in armour and resembling a walking tank - was highly likely to face a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a camouflage system used by many of today's animals.
Experts say this enabled him to blend in better with his surroundings and avoid his enemies, a camouflage system that suggests he was the favourite food of the larger dinosaurs.
Reports of the 110-million-year-old dinosaur family Nodosauridae first appeared in the paper in May. It is currently available for consultation at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Researchers named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who, along with the team, spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the wonderfully preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the patterns and shape of scales and armor all over the body.
They uncovered a camouflage method commonly used by today's animals to defend themselves - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this camouflage effect is common in nature, the researchers' findings are surprising because Borealopelta's size far exceeds today's animals using the same technique.
So it's possible that the dinosaur was so many predators that evolution preferred camouflage to confrontation in survival.
Many contemporary animals with camouflage - deer, zebra, or armadillo, for example - are much smaller and also more vulnerable to prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus had to literally fight for its survivors.
'The predation of a huge and heavily armoured dinosaur illustrates the danger posed by predators in the Cretaceous period,' said Brown.
Chemical analysis of the organic components contained in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur skin was likely reddish-brown in colour.
Researchers continue to study the animal, searching for more information about its life, including preserved stomach contents, to track down its last meal.
They believe the dinosaur fell into the river after it died and was carried to the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
The Alberta region at the time had the same climate as Florida today, and rivers and oceans stretched much farther inland than they do today.
'This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin while being preserved in three dimensions and so we can see its original size,' said Brown.
'For these reasons, the animal looks virtually the same as it did in the Cretaceous Age.
You don't have to use your imagination to reconstruct it; just squint a little and it seems as if he's just sleeping.'
In the Cretaceous period, giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs that moved on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the king of all dinosaurs - Tyrannosaurus rex - lived for several million years after Borealopelta, this armoured dinosaur may have been a favourite prey of his equally fearsome ancestors.
They include Acrocanthosaurus, an 11.5-meter-long monster weighing over 6 tons.
The researchers, whose most recent findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe the body of Borealopelt was washed into the sea after being mummified in mud.
Behind the find is Shawn Funk, who uncovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including leather and armor, which is also complete from snout to hip.
The animal was 5 meters in diameter and weighed up to 1,300 pounds.
Two 5-inch spines protruded from his shoulders.
Researchers believe this herbivore ploughed through what is now Canada until it ended up in a river that washed it out to sea.
His underwater tomb preserved the body in perfect condition.
The fossil remains of this species are also preserved to the extent that the armored plates around the skull still cover the remnants of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, finding such a surviving individual can be compared to winning the lottery.
The longer I watch him, the more shocking the find seems.
