A Becoming Resemblance: artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of one of the rooms of New York's Fridman Gallery are several faces of different skin tones - white, black and brown - suspended from the ceiling on wires, each one seeming to be the same as the last.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from swabs taken from her mouth and hair, sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for illegally leaking secret cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on 2 August, is entitled A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience with technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before he left the US presidency.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to represent what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a razor-sharp, if not intellectual, commentary on the pliability of DNA - as well as the many ways DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has talked since she was young about considering herself a woman, convicted in 2013 on 20 charges, including violating six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photographs were held by prison staff, and only one lower-quality black-and-white photo was leaked, showing Manning, visibly concerned, sitting in the driver's seat of the platinum blonde wig she is now associated with.
Positive reactions to Dewey-Hagborg's 2012 Stranger Visions project were still reverberating in 2015.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of possible likenesses of these people.
And it was around this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and they wanted to fill the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg explained at the opening of the new exhibition.
However, no visitors or photographs were allowed, so they approached Chelsea to ask if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
President Obama did ask for Manning's release days after the comic, a welcome change after a few excruciating years in a military prison in Kansas.
Indeed, it is interesting that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is at war with people who seek to make public government information and transgender soldiers, while trying to find new ways to stir up resentment in areas he should be encouraging with his tweets.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that "everything happens for a reason."
Under the declaration of an artist on one of the gallery walls, Manning's huge signature (the "i" in the surname is dotted with a heart) calls for the end of "self-indulgent factionalism that is based on gender, race, sexuality, and culture."
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a centipede of the letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated scientific vocabulary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate just how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"I hope people learn from this that our genome doesn't care who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and anyone can interpret it in their own way," Dewey-Hagborg said.
"DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last specimen of the exhibition, housed in a separate room, is a single page from the aforementioned graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging, King Kong style, from the United States Disiplinary Barracks Prison with a megaphone in her hand.
"Once they stop you from speaking, they win," it says.
"Never be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," said the Philadelphia artist.
"Thinking about it gives me the creeps."
Manning has not yet personally visited the exhibit - which was predicted in the comic book - but when she does, she will be greeted in the center of the room with her masks, her own genome effigies, lined up like a crowd of Protestants.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are penciled.
"They've been placed on walls in the past, but this time I wanted the feel of the crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted to create the impression of mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates her."
