'We will finalise WADA plan in the near future' - Russian Deputy Prime Minister Mutko
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko said it would not be long before the remaining World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) criteria were implemented and the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) re-established.
"Part of the criteria of the new plan have now been finalised and RUSADA has already been given the right to plan and test in cooperation with the UK Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
In light of this, the WADA plan has been updated," Mutko said on Thursday.
The Vice-President commented on the second part of WADA's plan to comply with the code - which describes the criteria for RUSADA's reinstatement - which was recently published on the organisation's website.
According to Mutko, the code contains nothing for Russia to worry about.
"Everything has been announced and will be implemented as well.
The results will be available to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA shortly," he added.
However, one of those criteria calls for a public announcement of the results of the WADA investigation, under investigation by Richard McLaren, into alleged government sponsorship of doping by Russian athletes.
On this subject, Mutko said: "We are conducting an investigation as our anti-doping system has clearly failed.
All measures have been taken.
But there were no state programs in our country, and we can't admit to something that never existed."
Vitaly Smirnov, director of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission, confirmed Mutko's words.
In an interview with Russia's RSport, Smirnov acknowledged the problems of Russian anti-doping officials, but added: "We have said on many occasions that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report completely unreservedly," Smirnov concluded.
WADA suspected RUSAD of carrying out doping controls within Russia in November 2015 immediately before the doping scandal.
Nevertheless, the organisation authorised the planning and unification of testing under the supervision of international experts and the UK Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD) in June this year.
Following a visit to the organisation's Moscow headquarters in July, WADA Director General Olivier Niggli said that RUSADA was "on the right track" to be reinstated.
