Creating a graphic novel: the story of A Castle in England
Scotney Castle, a small castle, recently played a starring role in the band's music video, Squeeze, and Margaret Thatcher also found refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
But Scotney witnessed 700 years of stormy history from his cozy spot by the Bewl River in Kent, Britain, which inspired the curly-haired Jamie Rhodes of York County - known for his fondness for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
"The sight of the writing of a man who is 300 years dead fascinates me," Rhodes says with a straight face.
"When I hold a letter in my hands, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of the families who lived in Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages until the Eduardo period, each story illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
But this is not Rhodes' first book inspired by the archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by British Library documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the '70s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
How I love archives!"
For someone who is so fascinated by old papers, the support from the National Trust and Arts Council England and being able to stay in the castle for almost four months is almost like a dream. ("To tell you the truth, I've extended my stay a little bit.")
Rhodes spent his time researching the Victorian "new" castle, going through archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on the wall and bottles that had been dumped in a ditch for centuries.
He wandered around the grounds, examining the ruins of the old castle, talking to gamekeepers, gardeners and, occasionally, artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
At night he would "drink whiskey and write."
The confidential history of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust did not gain access to the documents until 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site a decade later, the employees were just beginning to break into the archives, which Rhodes described in terms of "aristocrats of many centuries throwing their hands around saying, 'Take it to the attic.'"
Diaries, letters from the days of the British Empire, maps depicting fortunes: "You may think the land dispute is boring," Rhodes said, "but there was one case where two families fought over a birch tree.
Stop it, people!"
Some stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the English Rebellion of 1381.
"I found a record of a riot at the castle in 1380, which in the book was called the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex," Rhodes said.
"The English rebellion actually began in this area, and it occurred to me that the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they're connected after all."
The other stories are firmly linked to the castle's history - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by Darrell's family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled a coffin with stones (which wasn't discovered until years later after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes's favorite family are the Darrells: "I was intrigued by the male race - the men at the time were always in debt, spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family dealt with it by marrying rich or old ladies - handsome gentlemen, I imagine, who were fond of turning the heads of heiresses.'
With his stay at the castle over, Rhodes searches for more adventures.
He had recently returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he was soaking up inspiration for his next book on Elämänmäki, a former sanitarium from the early 20th century that had been swallowed up by nature.
But it is a special place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I thought, 'Now get the hell back to real life.'"
