For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests just the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel diseases.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million US residents and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are typically reminded not to eat meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in a protein helps to create immune cells that promote intestinal resistance.
Study leader Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the gut and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
When the scales tip to the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, researchers found the presence of body-tolerant immune cells in the stomachs of mice with a particular bacteria.
This bacteria requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to make cells.
Professor Colonna said: 'We found a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that promote body tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had.”
At the same time, he suggested that if the same turned out to be true for humans, a combination of L. reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory gut environment.
Post-graduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwaso, as part of a study of a type of body-tolerant immune cells, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice bred separately lacked the cells.
She deduced that one group of mice had a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of mice were tested by DNA sequencing, and researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
Mice that were bred in a sterile environment and lacked an intestinal microbiome - so they did not develop this kind of immune cell - were given L. reuteri bacteria - and developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers grew L. reuteri in the fluid and then transferred small amounts of fluid - bacteria-free - to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. At the same time, the number of cells fell by half after splitting doses of tryptophan.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us keep L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known if tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added, "Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control inflammation of the internal surface of the gut.
