White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to the South Lawn for last month's celebration of the American manufacturing industry came to $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of a July 17 program at the White House that showcased American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials surveyed a parade of products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn as part of an "emergency," said records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - the unit responsible for managing the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy's deputy commander for aviation the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7:00 p.m. on July 17 to mark the parade, scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and remain in place until the complete clearance of the entire site, which had been planned between 6:00 and 9:00 p.m.
The email went on to say that if there was a delay in departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be dispatched for the return flight due to working time regulations.
The original crew remained at the scene that evening, along with a helicopter and a unit of security personnel.
The records - obtained by TIME - did not show whether a second crew had been dispatched after all.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible violation of this regulation.
"We were wondering if this was a violation of the Hatch Act and were assured everything was in order," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you've been blocked," the second-in-command wrote back.
This "Made in America" parade was designated by the White House as an official event, and thus would not be covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
In attending the event, the president pushed for health-care reform that was moving through the Senate and talked about trying to rein in government regulations.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence purely for presentational reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered the check in February after the presidential plane taxied in the background at his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida. his Twitter account is abuzz with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
"The White House is pleased with the "Made in America" show, which featured products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials," said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often practice landing in the Washington area and on the South Lawn, practicing possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump was attending the G-20 summit in early July in Germany, HMX-1 made 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the crew's current training, a state official said.
The helicopter unit flew an additional eleven hours in "non-presidential support missions" on the same day.
The White House said no additional props were paid for with taxpayers' money.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company had no involvement in the negotiations for the helicopter's display on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the parade is difficult to determine, the Navy says.
According to the Defense Department, the hourly cost for fiscal year 2017, reimbursement of DoD expenses for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit records indicate a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
"Putting taxpayers' costs on the basis of estimates for reimbursements is very misleading," Walters said on the matter.
"These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual costs."
According to the 2015 RAND study, refunds for DoD expenses do not include personnel costs, but do include fuel, maintenance and contracted costs.
Then-White House Press Secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the parade.
"The idea of this week's show is to introduce products manufactured in the U.S.," Spicer said.
"I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut take great pride in the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state, and that they provide jobs for hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we pride ourselves on the helicopter and the other military installations that countless American citizens are involved in making.
It is appropriate to recall that fact.’
It's unclear if Trump was also looking at the helicopter when he made his rounds on the South Lawn, and all that can be said for certain is that he got behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky's representatives and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said, "I own three myself."
